        <DISPLAY_TIME>90.0 min</DISPLAY_TIME>
        <NOTES>Floral, resiny aroma and flavor. Primarily a bittering hop. Substitutes: Galena, Olympic.</NOTES>
      </HOP>
      <HOP>
        <NAME>Galena (US)</NAME>
        <ORIGIN>United States</ORIGIN>
        <ALPHA>13.0</ALPHA>
        <BETA></BETA>
        <AMOUNT>0.0226796</AMOUNT>
        <DISPLAY_AMOUNT>0.8 oz</DISPLAY_AMOUNT>
        <USE>Boil</USE>
        <FORM>Pellet</FORM>
        <TIME>60</TIME>
        <DISPLAY_TIME>60.0 min</DISPLAY_TIME>
        <NOTES>A cultivar developed in 1968 from Brewer's Gold by open pollination in Idaho. An open pollination means that the male hop is unknown. The alpha acid content is relatively high—11.5 to 13.5%—but its co-humulone content and its beta acid range are also high.</NOTES>
      </HOP>
      <HOP>
        <NAME>Amarillo (US)</NAME>
        <ORIGIN>United States</ORIGIN>
        <ALPHA>9.3</ALPHA>
        <BETA></BETA>
        <AMOUNT>0.01417475</AMOUNT>
        <DISPLAY_AMOUNT>0.5 oz</DISPLAY_AMOUNT>
        <USE>Boil</USE>
        <FORM>Pellet</FORM>
        <TIME>30</TIME>
        <DISPLAY_TIME>30.0 min</DISPLAY_TIME>
        <NOTES>Popular American mid-range alpha acid variety with a unique and distinct aroma discovered growing "wild" (spontaneously) in one of their hop yards and developed by Virgil Gamache Farms in late 20th century. Also known as VGX001, its strain number. It is registered Brand VGXP01 cv.</NOTES>
      </HOP>
      <HOP>
        <NAME>Cascade (US)</NAME>
        <ORIGIN>United States</ORIGIN>
        <ALPHA>7.0</ALPHA>
        <BETA></BETA>
        <AMOUNT>0.031184450000000002</AMOUNT>
        <DISPLAY_AMOUNT>1.1 oz</DISPLAY_AMOUNT>
        <USE>Boil</USE>
        <FORM>Pellet</FORM>
        <TIME>10</TIME>
        <DISPLAY_TIME>10.0 min</DISPLAY_TIME>
        <NOTES>Very successful and well-established American aroma hop developed by Oregon State University's breeding program in 1956 from Fuggle and Serebrianker (a Russian variety), but not released for cultivation until 1972. Gives the distinct citrus/grapefruit aroma to the Pale Ale produced by California's Sierra Nevada Brewing Company, the best-selling American pale ale in the country. One of the "Three Cs" along with Centennial and Columbus. Named for the Cascade Range. Substitutes: Centennial and Columbus (but they have a higher Alpha Acid content).</NOTES>
      </HOP>
      <HOP>
        <NAME>Crystal (US)</NAME>
        <ORIGIN>United States</ORIGIN>
        <ALPHA>4.5</ALPHA>
        <BETA></BETA>
        <AMOUNT>0.0170097</AMOUNT>
        <DISPLAY_AMOUNT>0.6 oz</DISPLAY_AMOUNT>
        <USE>Boil</USE>
        <FORM>Pellet</FORM>
        <TIME>5</TIME>
        <DISPLAY_TIME>5.0 min</DISPLAY_TIME>
        <NOTES>An American triploid variety developed in 1993 from Hallertau, Cascade, Brewer's Gold and Early Green. It is spicier than Hallertau (cinnamon, black pepper, and nutmeg). Substitutes: any Hallertau variety, Mount Hood, Liberty.</NOTES>
      </HOP>
      <HOP>
        <NAME>Crystal (US)</NAME>
